## 18) SCENE WRITING FORMAT

Use this exact format for each storyboard scene after the hook:

#### **SCENE [#] — [approx. time range]**
**CONTINUITY FROM PRIOR SCENE:**
- same worker
- same wardrobe and gear
- same location anchor
- same single lunch container
- same bag/cooler status

**NEW CHANGE IN THIS SCENE:**
- [only one main new action or development]

**VISUAL DESCRIPTION:**
[3–5 sentences of highly visual, cinematic description that can be directly converted into an image-generation prompt.]

**PROP LIMIT:**
- maximum 1 lunch container visible
- maximum 1 cooler/bag visible
- no duplicate food containers in frame

Each scene must clearly describe:
- environment / setting
- main subject
- exact action
- props / objects
- emotional tone
- lighting / atmosphere
- composition / framing
- story function in that moment
- what new pressure, failure, consequence, reaction, realization, or correction is being revealed

### Composition and continuity rules

- Write the visuals as a **Simpsons-style cartoon** with consistent character design across scenes
- The main character should usually take up **30–40% of the frame**
- The remaining **60–70%** should show the environment, tools, objects, supporting characters, or pressure source
- If another character appears, they must contribute to the story beat, not just fill space
- Preserve continuity of clothing, gear, cooler/bag status, weather, time-of-day, and emotional state unless the story intentionally changes them
- Frame transitions should feel smooth, like one storyboard flowing naturally into the next shot
- Adjacent scenes must look like slight camera shifts of the same unfolding moment
- Do not reintroduce the lunch setup as if it is a new object in each scene
- Keep hero props identical in color, size, shape, and condition across scenes
- Do not place duplicate versions of hero props in the background  ### Hand + prop simplicity rule

To reduce image-generation errors, each scene should show:
- one clear primary hand action
- one main prop interaction at a time

If the worker is holding the lunch container:
- do not also show them handling the drink, sandwich, radio, and bag at the same time

If another object matters, place it nearby rather than in hand.

Avoid overlapping prop interactions that can cause:
- duplicate lunch boxes
- repeated food items
- merged hands
- cluttered object layouts

Complex actions should be split across consecutive scenes instead of stacked into one frame.

### Visual negative constraints

Do not generate:
- duplicate lunch boxes
- duplicate coolers
- duplicate drinks
- duplicate sandwich bags
- repeated food containers
- extra background copies of the same prop
- floating or merged lunch items
- multiple opened/closed versions of the same container in one frame unless explicitly required

