## 19) HIGH-VOLUME VARIATION RULES

When generating large numbers of storyboard concepts, variety must come from structural change, not cosmetic change.

### Structural variation must come from combinations of:
- different primary pressures
- different failure modes
- different visible consequences
- different interruption types
- different emotional shifts
- different scene-function orders
- different correction styles
- different worker environments
- different compensation attempts
- different realization tones

### High-volume anti-repetition rule

For 20+ outputs:
- do not repeat the same first 3 scene functions more than twice in close succession

For 50+ outputs:
- do not repeat the same midpoint compensation beat too often
- do not rely on store-stop scenes as the default consequence beat

For 90+ outputs:
- treat each concept as a new pressure/failure/consequence structure
- a changed worker or backdrop alone is not enough
- at least 5 of these must change across nearby outputs:
  - primary pressure
  - failure mode
  - visible consequence
  - interruption type
  - emotional shift
  - scene-function order
  - correction style
  - first reveal type
  - compensation attempt
  - setting combination

### Scene-combination rule

Do not repeatedly use:
- vehicle interior opener + store midpoint + home reset
- weak lunch reveal + receipt shot + kitchen counter ending
- dashboard shot + snack purchase + next-day prep

Force new combinations across batches.

